"We are ready to protect them if it proves necessary."
The the University of The Ice
"University" of Bologna, it prepares the confectioners of ice the best seasons of the year.
The three-day training course held for the future of glaciers has been a great success and attracted visitors from around the world.
In fact, where does all the ice?
The Glacier and the ice machine.
The glacier, i.e., in German, the confectioner somewhat dated, ice cream factory in all the rules of Italian art of making the ice.
The turbine to remove ice cream of ice chilled using a spatula, available in the the waffle and then began to sell it.
To find out, there was no need to go to Anzola dell'Emilia in the Province of Bologna.
But anyone who wants to learn more about the ice, cannot avoid "Gelato-University" of the Italian firm.
The manufacturer of the sorbetières founded the University of ice in 2003 so that the ice cream out of its machines across the Italian ideals are high.
The three-day training course held for the future of glaciers has been a great success and attracted visitors from around the world.
Special courses are also available on the ice of chocolate and extending over several days, the practice sessions are held in the glacerie private.
Fully in midlife crisis, a number of people dream of a new career, others may simply to achieve their ardent desire on the ice smooth.
This time, it is 40 participants from 19 countries on all continents, Brazil to Saudi Arabia from Hungary.
Jacky, professor of education artistique come to California is a man of the Slow Food movement. it is to propose to the future a European product quality at countries of the Glace industrielle.
Anke of Berlin is a business management and it wants, after a few years, draw some strange thing of this trade experiencing nervine.
Two young Egyptian women dream of opening a glacerie in Cairo.
A man from Malta and another time Brazil would like to improve the quality of the ice cream in their bars, and the wife of Canadian household came because his children love the Italian ice cream.
The Master glacier Luciano Ferrari first explained participants the perfect ideal of perfect ice.
Is crucial not only the good flavour, but also the flexibility and the right consistency.
However, Luciano remember during the training the icing on the cake of the national superstructure and, in general, the south: "the Italian ice is simply the best: and then it still retains a sacrée dose of romanticism."
The first step in the production seems quite simple.
Luciano pays the basic ingredients, such as milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and Stabilizers in a large heat all to 85 degrees through a e-program, then cools immediately to four degrees.
He then opened a tap installed on the machine: it fate a basic white cream pasteurisée, basis for all sorts of ice to milk.
The trainer was immediately deluged with question: is it possible to manufacture the ice using only natural substances without?
How can we give free rein to the pleasure of the experiment?
Mr. Luciano cautions to be misled by the spirit of the times.
That only speaks of ice "made from natural ingredients," perhaps nevertheless used Stabilizers: the more often a natural product, for example flour guar seed obtained from the guar Bean.
It is of course possible to manufacture the ice without using a stabilizer only must sell it within 24 hours, otherwise it collapses and the client croquera does nothing other than ice pellets.
Some changes of the base mass are permitted.
This becomes more exciting with flavouring.
The Master Luciano makes the difference between the ingredients that it acquires in the fruit or radius of the supermarket.
In addition, there are the powder and pasta.
"Suppliers will try all of you passing dozens of aromatised ingredients."
"However, you should simply try."
In the fruit sorbets with sugar and fresh fruit.
In the cream made from the mass of white base, adding eggs becomes a yellow cream is, and when you add the cocoa powder, the basis of all possible desserts.
Now, all participants must switch to use ice machines.
Luciano invites them from time to time to produce four kinds of ice: in vanilla, chocolate and hazelnut moka in the with or without eggs in the mass of base, with more or less aroma of vanilla or other natural ingredients.
The different kinds of fruit ice are also subject to the same experience.
More aromatic substances, more fruit purees: from the perspective of taste, it is not absolutely best.
Hazelnut ice does not necessarily the taste of the nuts, when it is composed largely of hazelnuts.
The ice in kiwi, very popular, is made from the group using more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizing.
"Only a balanced mix properly is the taste of a lens," says Luciano.
The manufacture of ice is an exercise of calculation: if one uses the fishing purée with a lot of sugar, it is that the amount of sugar is reduced in the basic recipe.
Extra sugar is necessary for the lemon ice.
Luciano presents a device with which it determines the sugar content of different types of fruit (the vine-growers are used to measure the degree of Oechsle in the grape must).
Fortunately, the Tables facilitate the calculations.
The manufacture of ice no longer requires, as in the past, all physical intervention.
It is not just the automatic machine of the basic mass support.
There is also a device in which it fighting at the mixture of ice available to the buttery make and reduced to negative temperatures.
Despite all the automatisations, légères breakdowns are not excluded.
The Brazilian Gustavo is barbouille of fruit purée from head to toe and, thus, splashes his fellow students when control of the colossal mixer bowl escapes.
The master Luciano believes that "an incident like this could happen in every way: it is only a matter of time."
The controllers in an ambiguous position
According to some sources, the industry that experimented with the cultivation of genetically modified plants has hijacked the European Food Safety Authority.
This accusation is now made by the expert group Testbiotech, which is considered an independent institute for assessing the implications of biotechnology.
"It sounds like a conspiracy theory, but we well informed," said on Wednesday at Munich Mr. Christoph Then, Director of Testbiotech.
There are reports that the president of the group of experts Efsa for genetically modified plants, Mr. Harry Kuiper, as well as other experts Efsa are under contract with the pressure group Ilsi.
It is funded by groups such as Monsanto, Nestlé and Bayer.
Mr. Kuiper worked a critical role in the development of test requirements of the Efsa for genetically modified plants and is, therefore, clearly in a conflict of interest, according to the criticism by Mr. Then.
The requirements are verbatim, developed by subparagraphs, the positions of the pressure group Ilsi and bear the mark of the industry which, in essence, would be controlled by the authorities based in Parma in Italy.
It is the second time that Testbiotech denounced a conflict of interest.
A high-ranking official of the Efsa has recently joined unconditionally or without transitional period the Swiss food group Syngenta. in doing so, She has changed sides.
There is little time, even the Radio Central Germany Mitteldeutsche Rundfunk (MDR) had revealed the existence of personal relations between the authority of the European Union monitors and the industrial lobby, which has aroused the suspicions of both the German Federal Environment Agency that MEPs.
However, the Efsa admits the existence of no conflict of interest.
An opinion indicates that it operates all reliable data, including those of the industry as long as they are of good quality.
It does not prohibit experts working for the Efsa to establish contacts with the industry.
But they should make them public.
Mr. Kuiper admits that he worked for the International Institute for life sciences (International Life Sciences Institute, Ilsi) based in the United States.
The agency sees itself as a neutral forum bringing together experts who belong to, among others, the field of science, industry and politics in order to assess the risks of biotechnology without being in the pay of a lobby.
In this case, the independent experts such as Mr Then disapprove of the fact that the genetically modified plants are accepted without any testing of food in animals and that it was not tested the impact of these plants on the environment.
"We want to know what are, for example, the impact of genetically modified maize field cause," says Mr Then.
The current practice is to test only the proteins isolated and not the entire genetically modified plant, which does not obtain reliable results.
"If we do not seek the risks, how can we discover them?" asked Mr. Then on an accusatory tone.
It is also the view of Ms. Hilbeck.
This scientifique conducts research since 1994 in the field of genetics and is currently working at the Polytechnic of Zurich.
In this area, as in the United States, and now also in Europe, the industry is increasingly influence or discredit the scientific criticism.
That is why there is barely even researchers who are not related to companies.
In the view of companies, critical studies would not be published.
Ms. Hilbeck says that "the industry contrôle Security Research".
