Obama is a brake on new oil drilling
There will be no new oil drilling in the Gulf of Mexico off the coast of Florida State of the southeastern United States, in years to come.
The government of Washington delivered a ban A ban and, thus, definitely rescinded its original plans.
Even off the Atlantic Coast, new remain for the time being banned.
The Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar made the announcement Wednesday.
It is the explosion in April, the drilling rig Deepwater Horizon "who is at the root of this strict prohibition. it should remain in force at least for the next five years.
In response to the accident that claimed the lives of 11 employees and led to the largest environmental disaster of the United States, President Barack Obama, under pressure from the opposition and the industry, had indicated that he was willing to allow the completion of new drilling in the eastern Gulf of Mexico.
Proponents of this approach want to reduce U.S. dependence on foreign countries for oil supply.
The question of who is responsible for the devastating oil spill in the Gulf is not, to date, definitively resolved.
The British oil group, which is facing claims of several billion, is at the centre of the accusations.
A commission of inquiry set up by Obama must submit its conclusions in December.
In October, the Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar had lifted the freeze of drilling imposed after the explosion of the platform.
Following the decision, other oil groups had immediately submitted applications for new drilling projects.
With stricter controls and tougher safety briefings, Obama and Salazar want to prevent another disaster.
The competent authority, which was discredited after widespread allegations of corruption, is currently the subject of deep reforms.
Meanwhile, Mr. Obama announced the would remove the the lucrative oil and gas groups.
The players in this industry are now publicly warn that the flow of food in the Gulf would be significantly lower than is the case at present.
"The government's goal is to put a brake on the rapid growth of the oil and gas sector" as the result of a current survey carried out in the area by the audit firm BDO, before the drilling ban imposed on Wednesday.
Moreover, the American Enery Alliance deplores the uncertainty that characterized the sector: "no one knows what will change exactly with the regulation."
The investments made in support of new projects have been postponed until further notice, to the detriment of growth.
The Ogoniland is dry has
The water flowing into rivers is oiled brown; it smells similar to that which exists in the petrol station: because of a leak, billions of gallons of crude oil have destroyed the country Ogoniland in Nigeria.
Men are theft, corruption and oil refining.
Celestine Akpobari has a good intention.
"Don't épuisez," says the environmentalist to journalists for the calm: "you today still enough mud of oil before the lens of water."
The Nigerian 37 years tried to photograph a young sunk into the muddy water up to the chest, and drag the fat that surrounds it: this scene seems almost beautiful in the flash of water to the colour of the rainbow.
We cannot see that the basement is full of brown nappes of crude oil.
On the shore of the River Bodo-Jetty, Esther Badom said that once she was collecting shrimp by whole pails here.
But in the meantime the calm waters have completely dried up.
Five years ago, an enormous amount of oil has bounced a pipeline had exploded in the vast swamp.
The fishermen living in the small town near Bodo must now for six hours to reach the rich waters: the Ogoni located in the heart of the Niger Delta is considered one of the most polluted areas in the world.
The full extent of the devastation is blindingly obvious leafing through the mangrove swamps crossings by rivers.
Instead of clear water, the motorboat heartrending a brown water. anyone who plunges his hand the withdraws all covered in oil.
The roots of mangrove small emerge from the ground like licorice sticks. isolated palm trees are sadly hang their fins.
Looking in vain the clouds of birds, as it usually encounter in wetlands: as soon as the outboard engine stops, a ghostly silence descends on the haven of old who resembles a gas station by the smell that it evokes.
"What happens here is war against the environment," said Mr. Celestine Akpobari with a sadness: "our life is characterized by a permanent danger with regard to health."
The comparison of wars is made.
The region where the Ogoni is a battlefield besieged for decades: more than 60 years ago, the first European explorers have entered here; the first was organized resistance in the 1980s by the writer Ken Saro-Wiwa. it was executed later. in 1993, the Shell Group had to interrupt its production activities in this region because they had become very dangerous for its employees.
Even today, the Ogoni returning is prohibited in this society: while more than 2 million barrel of black gold daily are pumped through more than 5,000 wells and 7,000 kilometres of pipelines in the entire region of the Delta, three times as large as Switzerland, the oil fields are undeveloped Ogoni, because the situation is too unstable for the oil group.
Every few hundred metres stand in water of steel sculptures as bizarre sculptures: it means very affectionately "Christmas trees" the head of drill holes.
They had up to 50 years, most are riddled by corrosion to the landmark.
Akpobari believes that a drilling head of this nature breaks from time to time in piece, as a constant flow of crude oil flows through the water.
According to expert estimates, more than two billion litres were dumped on the ecosystem in 50 years: each year, the equivalent to the amount of oil that leaked into the sea at the Exxon Valdez accident "super-pétrolier" 21 years ago off the coast of Alaska, one of the biggest environmental disaster in the history of humanity.
That should be the responsibility of the continuing environmental pollution? the answer to this question divides the actor.
For the group Shell, sabotage and the siphonage pipelines are responsible for more than 90 percent of the pollution. environmentalists for their part consider the explosions of rock-drilling warheads and perforated pipelines punctured as the main causes.
In 2008, the American scientist Richard Steiner criticized the Shell Group to apply in Nigeria to enforce safety standards mostly less strict than elsewhere in the world: only the rate of failures of pipes is "still much higher than alleures".
Some emerging forms of Mangroves in a place that, seen from afar, resembles a workshop abandoned, full of cambouis and installed in the open air: they are completely naked and covered in cambouis up to the neck.
A scintillating fire in one of the many tons that sometimes associated with pipes, sometimes scattered without ground on the site must be répérés: a small refinery underground.
It is heat the crude oil in the barrel for several hours, "says Michael, the team leader.
As a first step, gasoline enters a container through pipes, then, at the end of the conduct of kerosene drops fall and it finally obtained diesel.
This is as well that Michael and his four colleagues produced daily four barrels of Diesel 300 litres: "we reported 34 million Naira", about $22.
The inhabitants of the Delta take advantage of the chronic shortage of fuel in the largest oil producing country in black Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
Illegal refiners can sell at a price less expensive than ridiculously low of just 40 euro cents per litre of Diesel: free as they become the raw material.
It is offered by the "protectors" who put the network of Unlocks pipeline across the country of the Ogoni. according to the experts, the country loses in this way at least 16 million gallons of crude oil in the whole of the Niger Delta.
Only a small part quite insignificant of the raw material is temporarily stored illegally purified: organized crime rings that are also among its members of politicians and senior military, load the lion's share in tankers and the bradent in the global market.
The activist Akpobari believes that the debate on the question of whether to award the environmental disaster or rather subversive activities to the public or the mode of production latitudinarian is purely academic.
"If the oil companies were not seen as intruders and if the foundations of the lives of fishermen were not so deeply destroyed, there could be no sabotage or theft and illegal refineries."
But, Meanwhile, the relationship of the Ogoni especially to Shell have so much that it was no longer question that the withdrawal of the group. "perhaps that operators with other nationalities, such as the Chinese, will prove to be better."
So, Michael becomes nervous.
"It is high time that you déguerpissiez" announcement the robust oil worker.
"The soldiers can occur at any time."
If the illegal refiners are surprised by special units of the armed forces, they will certainly not under arrest, but at most they will offer bribes.
Even the soldiers especially from the north of the country will benefit as all Nigerians as the raw material.
"At any point of view, this fucken trick brought down our country well low", Akpori regrets.
