However, this technique is valid since the 1950s.
The CIA has shown a video presentation with satellite images blur.
Through computer-assisted animation, it indicated the likely location of each component of the reactor before the destruction of the station, which is a miniature copy of the model nord-Coréen of the Yongbyon nuclear facility.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the nearby building, even internally.
It seems that the reactor was about to be put into service, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombardment, it has barely more information that at the time, and even, with the time the mystery deepens increasingly.
Former US President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that before the attack, the CIA was sure that Syria had built a reactor to el-Kibar peu', but had evidence that country was developing "an active nuclear weapons."
Some intelligence officers in Europe prefer to be more careful about this and speak only of an alleged "reactor", even though they view the presentation of the CIA as "plausible".
They lack of evidence, as well as the IAEA.
Asked about the way it ensures that it is dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior diplomat of United Nations only gave a terse response in summer by stating that the IAEA had "sufficient documents to ask questions".
The Syrians have certainly removed with haste the rubble of "unused military building" methodical and made a levelling off of the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen, discovered el-Kibar traces of uranium produced by men.
In addition, the IAEA has received through a Member State of commercial providers of satellite images showing the moment that followed directly the attaque. it seems that they are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, has acquired in exclusivity.
It is impossible for the IAEA to determine their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always ensured that she had never made a secret atomic programme and that it had not built reactor.
Damascus maintains that the uranium found on the site comes from the weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA has rejected that argument after analysis of particles calling it was implausible.
Since that time, damas refuses any discussion in that, as well as on satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow controllers to conduct a second inspection on the site of el-Kibar and access to the rubble of the destroyed building by the bomb.
But even Israel remains a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister at the time of the attack, said recently: "we will never comments on this issue.
It is as well that the investigation of this case has been dragging on since June 2008 without that there was a result and that it "is increasingly becoming a serious problem of credibility of the Agency", as the recognizes a senior Western diplomat in service to the IAEA in Vienna, ultimately it is a serious violation of the treaty banning nuclear weapons.
The IAEA believes that to make progress, we must clarify the existence of three other facilities that must have "a functional relationship" with the alleged reactor.
Until now, the inspectors have not specified what it is facilities here, nor what is their function or have it may contain.
According to information published by the newspaper Süddeutsche Zeitung, "these are known within the IAEA respectively under the names of Marj as-Sultan Iskandariayah, Iskandariayah, and also the name of neighbouring towns.
The Independent Institute Institute for Science and International Security (International Institute of Science and International Security in Washington has identified these locations and discovered on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that would most probably one suspicious objects.
It is possible that it is on a military base or directly beside it; this is exactly why Syria refuses access of three sites to IAEA inspectors.
In Vienna, it says that the Syrians fear that the group of inspection is in fact spies that would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on its military installations.
Indeed, it is an information provided by the US secret agents who attracted the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has the information, including satellite photos indicating that vehicles have been shuttling between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped to carry substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could be used in the production of fuel ".
He would have "no indications on sensitive activities," such as the enrichment and reprocessing of uranium; processes that are essential to the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor is certainly operates through not enriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there is the rigour of plausible assumptions concerning the basic questions: where should have come and where uranium or plutonium separated later needed for the production of the bomb.
It is unclear if the rubble, which could hide traces of great value, were stored at the three sites.
When the hundreds of truckloads of land will have disappeared, nobody will have information on repository of rubble.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria has made review in 1998 the salt-mine of al-Tibni, located only a few miles from el-Kibar, the other side of the Euphrates, to see if we can agree the storage of radioactive waste.
