The democratic Routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as to private enterprise.
The crime has become a greater concern as unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarómetro poll taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Given that the survey was done regularly since 1995, it tracks changes in attitudes in the region.
Two elements stand out the results of the survey this year, conducted in September and early October.
The first is quite sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased to a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy rebounded after suffering a sharp drop in production last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries of the region, are convinced democrats, which lowers the average régionale (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents across the region are satisfied with the way democracy in their countries worked in practice; it is the same number as last year but with a sharp increase on the 25 per cent in 2001 (Chart 3)
Some 34% said that they had confidence in Parliament of their country and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but in sharp rise compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
Ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America have undermined support for democracy.
If it held good during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries of America experienced only a brief recession and have benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a network of social security network helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year, at 32 percent.)
But the mood varies greatly from one country to another (see chart 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is a widely shared sense of progress
What is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and where violent crimes escalated.
This is only for the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited the crime rather than the unemployment as the most important issue for their country (see Table 5).
Approximately 31% say that they or their relatives have been the victim of a criminal act in the past year; however, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in rising support for private enterprise and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is indispensable to the development, against 56% in 2007 (see chart 6).
Some 58% felt that the market economy is the only system that will make their developed country, against 47 per cent last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% supported the private company); even if their left-wing president, Hugo Chavez, expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, mentioned by 19 per cent of respondents (against 18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent, down 11 per cent since last year)
But the United States is considered the most influential countries by respondents in Mexico and throughout much of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
