Nobody was expecting to have perfect general elections in Haiti on 28 November.
But it was far worse than the "outsiders" who wanted to help the stricken country and plunged in fear.
It was presented with ballot boxes, and a new voting, ballot papers scattered in the goutières, PSs ransacked and intimidation
Polling stations opened late in the evening.
Many Hatïens, including many who were displaced following the earthquake in January, walked in the neighborhood to find where to vote.
Some of them were eventually abandoned.
A dozen presidential contenders, including several alleged favourites, have denounced the fraud and called for the annulment of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, exploded across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the top official in Haiti to the United Nations, sees the event as "an election fairly good in many ways."
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community said cautiously that they "do not believe that these irregularities, as serious as they are, necessarily had invalidated the process".
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are indebted to René Préval, Past-President impopulaire, and its candidate, Jude Célestin, must announce preliminary results on 7 December.
The expected second round is scheduled for January.
Any hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rap musician, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial appeal for the vote to be annulled.
But there may be problems if Mr. Célestin, who has little or no discernible support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second toura reached the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and more than 1 million in earthquake survivors who are still living in tents, it was feared that participation would be.
In the case, many Haitïens wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of the disruption.
Nearly 250,000 identity cards, necessary to vote, were not yet distributed shortly before the election.
The issue is important.
Donors see the election of a popular government legitimate and as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And so, it is clear, Haitians are doing it themselves.
Point feet toward the Centre
The weeks after becoming suddenly widow, Cristina Fernández, president of Argentina, has benefited from a wave of sympathy from the public that has improved its approval rate of 20 points, to more than 50 per cent; it is his highest level since it was elected in 2007.
Yet turn this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year could depend on the choice of Ms. Fernández, visibly in mourning, that it would leave or not the intransigence of her late husband and predecessor, former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this respect, the signs are still confused.
Mr Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy, even after his wife succeeded him as president, used to develop budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This has allowed the first couple to spend the extra money at will.
Ms Fernández's government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has sunk into disarray following the death of Mr Kirchner of a heart attack on 27 October.
Some of the dissenting members of the movement péroniste have rallied to Mrs. Fernández.
But after meetings (where a chaotic parliamentary struck in the face with one of its peers and where others have accused the government of corruption), Congress does not to approve the 2011 budget.
"I am not going to play," said the President.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the President even greater leeway to spend at will.
The economy overheating widely: it is likely to grow by nearly 9 per cent this year.
The official rate of inflation is now at 11.1% but many private estimates and the wage demands of unions, see this figure close to 30%.
Mr Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, has made a priority of growth and poverty reduction, rather than the control of inflation.
He has refused to deal with the IMF, he harassed the private sector and served the INDEC, the statistical office, who proceeded to the falsification of the official inflation.
Ms Fernández could now moderating these policies?
It called for talks between private companies and union leaders.
And officials say they want to limit the wage increases next year to 6 per cent.
The economy has been driven by high world prices for Argentina's farm exports.
But inflation has eroded the boost to growth following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps that is why Ms Fernández has shown signs of wanting to re-establish financial relations of Argentina to the rest of the world.
This year, the government has reached an agreement with bondholders who had rejected an earlier restructuring forced the debt on which Argentina had not paid its milestones in 2001.
Now Ms Fernández seems to be edging towards an agreement with garanti governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this would not involve monitoring by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Amado Boudou, the Economy Minister, announced that the Fund would provide a "technical assistance" to design a new national index of consumer prices; what looks like a prelude to clean the INDEC.
It is not clear whether Ms Fernández is to remain in politics beyond the end of his term, now that her husband is no longer at his side.
If it does, it needs to win the support of the middle class, among which the kirchnerisme is very advocated.
When Argentines will be returned from their summer holidays in March, the wave of sympathy for it will have returned.
If it wants to win another election, it will have to decide to repudiate or not, without noise, many policies of her husband.
