In any case, said Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PDP, murder has had an impact on the election by leading the suspicion on the DPP and turning voters towards the KMT.
Perhaps the biggest winner of the elections was China.
It was striking how the issue of mainland itself was absent.
Instead, the candidates have jouté with plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan generally enjoys its de facto independence and dislikes the military threat from China.
Thus, the KMT tends to avoid displaying its links with the government in Beijing.
But this time, the DPP has also failed to stir up anti-Chinese sentiment.
This is the response to a new awareness that Chinese companies are essential to the economic survival of Taiwan.
Mr. Ma, for its part, has claimed a confirmation on whether its policy on China was acceptable to the majority of Taiwan.
It is expected that the government in Beijing continues to provide commercial facilities, in line with its strategy to lure Taiwan, of homecoming.
China lost no time to send a negotiator in Taipei to organize a summit on the protection of investments and medical cooperation.
Of course, she would also like to see a political integration; but let's start at the beginning.
Better to wait until after the presidential election in 2012.
The DPP has reinvented anyway.
Two years ago, it went wrong: his former chief, Chen Shui-bian, was sent to prison on corruption charges.
President from 2000 to 2008, he was a troublemaker in favour of an explicit independence.
But a new generation of moderates saw the day under the direction of Ms. Tsai and PDP makes every effort to attract professionals and young people.
Ms. Tsai has been hailed as a candidate of the DPP to the Presidency, as Su Tseng-chang, who served under Mr Chen.
Their party is doing its best to show that it, too, can engage with Beijing.
Ms. Tsai has announced plans for a panel of experts to act as a point of contact between the DPP and China, provided that their talks can take place without preconditions.
Ms. Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that his party has an "alternative trustworthy" from the hasty approach Mr. Ma on China.
Mr. Chen is exasperated by this change.
In a statement issued from his cell, he said that the candidates of the PDP would have achieved better results if they had insisted that Taiwan is a separate country.
He has even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatic, not to run for the presidency.
Even without the intervention of Mr Chen, the DPP will struggle to choose between its potential candidates.
The need for the KMT introspective of himself.
