A microbe tolerant arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, broadens the scope to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although the researchers found the bacterium unusual here on Earth, they say it shows that life has opportunities beyond the major elements that were considered essential.
"This organization has a double capacity."
"It can be developed with phosphorus, either with arsenic."
"That is why it is very special, even if it is far from being a form of life form" étrangère "," commented Paul Davies C. W. of the University of Arizona State, co-author of the report in the online edition of the journal Science on Thursday.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, nitrogen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But the researchers found that the bacteria discovered in the Mono Lake in California, is able to continue to grow after replaced phosphorus by arsenic.
"We wondered what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond the Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, to know what life is like, said Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss this, which has not disclosed the details of the find, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This was not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other global environments, the agencies could be able to use other elements to actuate the biochemistry and that the whole" standard "elements, that we are absolutely necessary for life, could not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute of Scientific Research planétaire and spacial, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in basic biochemistry and the biochemical structure," added Cockell.
This was not a fortuitous discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the Institute of NASA Astrologie, who led the study, chose the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, it has been speculated that a microbe exposed to the two substances might be able to substitute one to the other.
Arsenic is poisonous "mainly because its chemical behaviour is very similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, the agencies have difficulty distinguishing these components separately."
"But the arsenic is sufficiently different to that it doesn't work exactly as phosphorus; it cuts inside and, in a way, the work of our gum biochemical machine," said Anbar.
The researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and have exposed to increasing concentrations of arsenic in which she was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic in the place raises the possibility that some form of life using arsenic can occur naturally or else on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic may be replaced by phosphorus, was not new, but nothing has ever shown that this could walk.
Arsenic was more frequent at the beginning of the existence of the earth, she says; therefore, the researchers hypothesized that the first life forms could use.
This suggests that there may be other ways to form life, not just how life on Earth was formed at the beginning, "said Foster, who was not part of the research team of Wolfe-Simon.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
