The lion is ready to again blush, the restructuring of MGM is no longer expected that the final go-ahead to the Court
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM has finally been given the green light to start from scratch.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York, has officially praised Thursday the plan "pre-packaged" by the creditors that approximately $5 billion of debt would be erased; paving the way for the entertainment company, with 86 years of existence, to concentrate its efforts on the production and distribution of films and television programs.
With the decision on Thursday that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, no legal obstacle does remain before MGM to recover afloat under the tutelage of the founders of Spyglass Entertainment, Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who become the Directors-General of what will be a studio eased.
Staff will be reduced to approximately 320 on 400 at the outset.
MGM will not emerge really Chapter 11 as JPMorgan Chase will not have concluded a credit facility of $500 million, expected to fund the new operations and productions of MGM.
It is currently distributed under licence by the investment bank, which itself faces to 75 million, and should be financed by mid-December.
The process of restructuring the studio began in May 2009 when the investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise the direction on how to place its finances as it did not have the means to pay the interest amounting to $300 million a year.
In August, the Director General, Harry Sloan, was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO of Enron and an expert in reorganization known for his work with Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Attempts to Moelis and Cooper to solve the financial difficulties of MGM and satisfy the more than 140 creditors of the studio have taken much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties have agreed, at the end of 2009, putting the company up for sale.
However, the auction has attracted few bidders including none of them was willing to pay $2 billion more in which creditors were looking.
In the spring of this year, it was all re-conduct while the team of MGM had started working on a restructuring plan which, after months of disagreements and internal debates, has finally been approved by creditors at the end of October.
When MGM officially fate of bankruptcy in the following weeks, companies Moelis and Cooper receive bonuses of several million dollars for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
The companies of Cooper, who had collected $375,000 per month for their services management of the company, will receive a "success" bonus of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum account boost production of MGM, which has released only one movie this year, and set up an annual list of seven or eight films that would graduate from 2012.
They also intend to co-finance two films based on "the", with Warner Bros
The studio must conclude a separate loan from $265 million and $275 million to fund its share of these two films, which must be carried out by Peter Jackson.
The investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18 per cent of MGM's debt, has tried to achieve a merger of the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the largest shareholder.
However, the recent discussions between the two companies had not reached an agreement.
