Prosecutors do not inculperont senator Ensign
Justice prosecutors have lifted the criminal charges brought on Senator John Ensign, arising from a case linked to an assistant of a former campaign and its efforts to obtain a lobbying work for the husband of the woman, have announced Wednesday, lawyers for the Senator.
The decision puts an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, Republican of Nevada who was seen as a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case is the national headlines last year and hurt his career.
The office of Mr. Ensign said he was "very pleased" by the decision, the result of an investigation of a year.
Senator could still be at risk of disciplinary action taken by the Senate ethics committee.
Lawyers for Mr. Ensign said that the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign did more investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case."
The Ministry of Justice has refrained from comment on this subject.
The announcement came as something of a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, that there would be significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign would have conspired to violate a ban on lobbying federal criminal.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first disclosed in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain a lucrative lobbying work to earn the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the case of Senator with it.
Ms. Hampton had once served as treasurer in a campaign of Ensign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political donors to find work for Mr. Hampton, and then he defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to the documents and interviews.
Given that Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was banned for a year by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual arrangement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the case, seems at odds with the prohibition of the so-called revolving door of lobbying.
According to the evidence that has been made public, "there seems to be a prima facie case of a plot to rape and material breach of the law of the revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of an investigation by the government.
Although the judge of the department had declined to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the case of Ensign, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers have said that the department appeared to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of setbacks high-level cashed in his section of the public integrity, including the decision last year to abandon the prosecution against former senator Ted Stevens accused of misconduct of prosecution.
Federal prosecutors have clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a group of défense who has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, lead counsel for Mr. Ensign, said in an interview on Monday that he had received a telephone call from a prosecutor of the Ministry of Justice and up the next day, saying that the department was not trying to charges against his client.
The team of lawyers from Mr. Ensign had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the Senator, as his office reiterated Wednesday in a news release, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments it had made to prosecutors.
"I am not comfortable to go into the details of my discussions with the Ministry of Justice, except to say that we believe they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission has decided to abandon an investigation following a complaint by the independent ethics group, arguing that the payment of $96.000 by parents of Mr. Ensign to the Hampton violated federal election law.
The electoral commission said that it did not enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a large company of Nevada who has long supported Senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton to find lobbying work.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company hosted Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, the Chief of Staff of Mr. Ensign, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told her that he "martelait" the Department of the Interior on an issue.
Mr. Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another client of Nevada, Allegiant Air, and it has asked the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after hiring Mr. Hampton to lobbying.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his position as the leader in Republican ranks fourth in the Senate.
Having kept a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intends to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was not the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said that the Senator had hoped that the ethics committee quickly would follow the example of the Department of Justice and put an end to its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
The appeal of Cheshire will flow to Twitter
Half a dozen of them were in the process of typing away in rows of the courtroom.
They sent all the minutes of reports of horrific testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defence has said that there are more than 140,000 messages on the trial of the case of rape and children tied to their beds in a house which was set on fire.
Thursday, the trial widely followed by Steven J. Hayes, who has been convicted of killing three members of the family in Cheshire, Connecticut, is expected to lead to a formal end where the judge would impose the death penalty, passed by the jury.
But lawyers for Mr. Hayes had already submit any charting arguments to the court of appeal, likely to occupy the courts for years.
What is provocative, it is that the intense coverage of the trial - as well as widespread use and extended by journalists of the Twitter - have created a "circus atmosphere," a saturation so widespread and instantaneous with incendiary details that the jury was improperly influenced by the passions of the public.
The request could push the appeal judges to discuss the question of whether the new technologies require new rules in the courtroom.
"I have experience during the trial; I think there's a real danger, the introduction of new technologies in the courtrooms violates the rights of the individual to a fair trial," said Thomas J. Ullmann, a lawyer for Mr. Hayes, chief lawyer.
The trial judge, Jon C. Blue of the Superior Court of State answers, has rejected the claims in the judgement last week, saying that the media were "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the board would have been led by the passion.
But that does not seem to be the last word on the issue.
The appellate courts have recognized for decades that the media coverage of notorious cases may raise questions about the fairness of the trial.
In a judgment of landmark 1966, the United States Supreme Court has overturned the conviction of an osteopath of Cleveland, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, supporting in its decision that there was a "carnival atmosphere at trial" because the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the TV show and film "The fugitive".
Some lawyers have said that the courts of appeal for review seized half a century later the conviction of Mr. Hayes may be curious given the argument that new rules could be needed to manage the means of communication courtrooms, unimaginable at the time of the case of Dr. Sheppard.
"There is a general reason to worry about the impact of new media" in the large-scale trial, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at the Stanford Law School who has studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it has been applied arbitrarily.
Professor Donohue says some appeal judges could be intrigued by the idea that the limitation of instantaneous communication from courtrooms could allow more just trial.
The case of Twitter is one among many others described by lawyers for Mr. Hayes, likely to be discussed for years; which is delaying the execution.
Defence lawyers also claim, for example, that Mr. Hayes would have suffered harm when the judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reaction of potential jurors by showing them lurid photos of crime scenes in the selection of the jury.
Some jurors said they were horrified by the photos of victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11 years.
Defence lawyers argue that they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and they will argue that the judge was unfairly evicted the juror, who had been critical to prosecutors, and that he improperly put pressure for a verdict in taking the unusual step of getting the jury to deliberate in a weekend.
The jurors were not sequestered.
But their arguments on the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the greatest source of interest.
They noted in a challenge against the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and that it was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They maintained that the computer media continued to fan the flames of the emotion of the case.
"The stampede of media daily tweets, cameras and journalists in front of the courthouse," wrote lawyers, "does resembled nothing had been seen here in New Haven, and perhaps even to the national level."
Their emphasis on the cover of the Twitter system is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists have said that the claim that the instant new releases were more incendiary that recovered more slowly, was a view luddiste that would impoverish the policy of the Court for media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers have said that the courts of appeal étaitent often attracted to the arguments that the social and technological change required an adaptation by the courts.
Lawyers for Mr. Hayes insist on this claim.
In their case, they refer to the Supreme Court decision of 1966 who had reversed the conviction of Dr. Sheppard because of the media coverage of the trial and they indicated that they would use the need for new rules for the new media.
"This case," écrivaient-ils ", represents the Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st Century."
Civility can bridge the divides?
After a campaign marked by the invective and the negativity, a modicum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of a genuine bipartisan cooperation to the front or a time illusory before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and congressional leaders of Congress produced no breakthrough on the key issues that need to be addressed during the session of the "lame duck".
But clearly, there are at least had a polite discussion on differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibility to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to score empty marks. scoring point supporter.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the commission on the deficit of the president has been equally civilized, despite political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect across the ideological divide; but, however, still divides members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two parties are now in a period of trial and mutual tested for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the meeting on Tuesday and the subsequent comments were unveiled a minimum requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed in the past two years.
Whether taxation, spending, health care or the rights, the two parties remain of miles away.
Yet, the election of November had moderate Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed on the tone," said Pete Wehner, an official of the Bush administration, now at the side of the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"It is inevitable after the election.
The elections are partisan passions, and then they estomptent.
This is good. "
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and nobody is in favour of it.
Both parties want to find a way to keep some or all, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, not least because the Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing the unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After the meeting on Tuesday at the White House, more optimism flat on a possible agreement on issues raised during the session on the "lame duck", with the ratification of the pact "New START".
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution, warns that a fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the session "duck" blade ménera does not necessarily a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that need to be made will be the psychology in the short term will revert to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner has also expressed scepticism that the widely shared civilité would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I think most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pré-spectacle or a shadow-boxing over the main event in 2012, he said.
The reasons are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present tea which contributed to its creation.
But Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they should try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and to repeal the new law on health care.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Committee of the deficit which include reform the tax code and to increase some taxes, raise the retirement age and cut expenses.
The co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have imposed on themselves, imposed the issue of the shortfall on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes to the committee, composed of 18 members, to submit their plan as a formal recommendation, and they have struggled to reach this number.
The greater resistance remains among the elected representatives of the group, suggesting that there is on tax matters, at least today, little reasons or willingness to compromise.
Galston provides two phases in the fighting between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of clashes supporters, given that Republicans oppose Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; and then be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of Change?
Public public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still wants to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, when the two parties will watch carefully the public's reaction.
That will be tried in loss should change course and seek compromise.
But it will be an optimistic view.
The partisanship and polarization are larger now than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a more ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress that there were between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a larger election in 2012.
Given this reality, civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take a lot more effort on the part of both parties to find common ground on issues that divide them.
The American documents disclosed describe Moscow as a haven of Corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a "Kleptocratie" and pushed up in the Kremlin part bribes and money of protection that it collects, reported the U.S. Embassy in Russia in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service rackets are making huge that help to explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They are raising money not only of legitimate companies but also of organized criminal groups.
Each layer of bureaucracy - the Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the "vertical of power" - takes its share, while the money went to the top of the scale.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name Ambassador John Beyrle, was mailed Wednesday by Wikileaks on its Web site.
The Note is based on sources whose names have been removed.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and it is largely responsible for corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there has since been little trace of cleaning.
Luzhkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a construction business leader, have always denied the accusations of corruption over the years; and he has won several libel trial on those charges.
In September, he said the following to a Russian TV channel, when he was asked about a documentary suggesting that he was corrupt: "it is crazy, it is to lay, it is anything."
The Russians believe, an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt; according to the polls.
But it is unusual to find the information contained in a report of embassy; and it is incredible to think that this would be to diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link established between the government of the City of Moscow and crime has led some people in the name of "dysfunctional" and to say that the government functioned more as a kleptocracy that a government ", according to the notes of the Embassy.
The criminal elements enjoy "krysha" (a term used in the criminal world / the mafia which literally means "roof" or protection) passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Department of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor's office, as well as through the bureaucracy of the government of the city of Moscow.
"Analysts to identify a three-tier structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The FSB, the MVD and the militias are the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"It is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fills a void in some areas where the city does not provide some services."
The report states that the FSB breaststroke money from the larger companies and that the police are targeting small.
A source, he said, "explained that the Moscow business owners understand that it was better to obtain protection from the FSB and MVD (rather than organized crime groups) because, not only, they have more weapons, more money and more power than the criminal groups, but they are also protected by the law."
"That is why the request for protection by criminal gangs is not so high."
The note said that, although the collection money should be extended, the protection itself can be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subjected to an arrest.
Those who do not pay their quickly close under any pretext or another.
Medvedev referred to several times the fight against corruption, but he admitted the little progress.
The notes of the embassy transmits reports of men who bring suitcases, probably filled with money, to the Kremlin.
"In its fight against corruption, Medvedev depends on bureaucrats," said in a recent interview Gueorgui Satarov, Director of the Indem think tank "of Moscow.
"But it is part of the bureaucracy."
"It is not part of a political class because they do not exist in Russia."
Without politics, without opposition, no separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
According to the Indem, the costs of corruption would be on the scale of Russia as a whole, to more than $300 billion a year.
The country has been ranked 154th in a recent survey on the overall perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (the countries are ranked at least in more corrupt).
The disclosure of the note of the American Embassy, which was was carried out yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, remuera with certainty of discontent within the Russian government; although Luzhkov can be blamed, in part, to the failures of Moscow, this could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to show that he is in the process of solving the problem.
Interviewed by CNN by Larry King, Putin has speculated that the WikiLeaks documents could be a manufacturing and reacted with anger to the point that U.S. diplomats had disclosed in the appellant Batman and Robin closer Medvedev.
"The problem is based on the fact that it is our interaction, important factor in domestic politics in this country," he says.
"But to be honest with you, we do not suspect that it would be done with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, in opposition to ethics."
Veterans of the Khmer Rouge forced to confront the past
In a classroom poorly lit with concrete walls decrepit of poor quality, the director of the school in Anlong Veng referred to the man who had built, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here like Ta Mok."
"It was a good leader; and he cared for his people," said Sreng Kor Sreng, aged 42.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was the head of the Khmer Rouge, the commander remains popular in this isolated former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where it has built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge went to the government, the longtime loyalty is finally called into question at Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum of truth and reconciliation allowed the victims to respond publicly to people who had participated in the plan.
In June, the government has distributed a manual of high school that, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to children of its former soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court, jointly run with the United Nations, made its first sentence for a former member of the Khmer Rouge, condemning, to 35 years in prison, the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture centre, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as "Duch".
Before this, anxiety has increased with veterans of the Khmer Rouge of Anlong Veng, complicating the reconciliation efforts and their wishes to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything," said Youk Chhang, director of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia, an independent organization that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"The situation is divisions within the family."
During the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease and overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and toppled the government of Pol Pot-Unis in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army have fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There, they launched an insurgency that lasted until the last movements of visit in December 1998.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, Ieng Sary headed the guerrillas from their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a response to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the United Nations has led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect to the government, culminating with the capitulation of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had held head, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without their benefactors, most former Khmer Rouge fighters have sunk in abject poverty, common in rural areas of Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic of the movement.
Although a few elite officers Khmer Rouge have kept their posts of local leader in exchange for having laid down their arms, it is farmers not qualified in low rank and file.
"These people have benefited from very shortly after the capitulation," said Leang Sok-to of the Centre for justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are soaked in agrarian utopist ideology of the regime."
"They were raised in an environment where business is a foreign concept."
Sor Lim, aged 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as'adolescent in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok feeds everyone."
But now, life is difficult because we need to meet our own needs. "
The Khmer Rouge tribunal has also provoked concerns here.
The court should, at the beginning of next year, begin the trial of Nuon Chea Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge Minister.
The Court's mandate is to try senior leaders and most responsible for crimes, but he has not said if it continues beyond these four cases.
It should be more to calm fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation turned to Im Chaem, aged 64, former district chief in the province of Banteay Meanchhey under Khmer Rouge rule in the 1970s.
In 2007, she said researchers of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia that she had supervised the construction of the dam of Trapeang Thma, a project where thousands of forced labourers were killed.
Recently, in a torrid evening, Im Chaem returned from work in the field near his wooden house on stilts, on a dirt road outside of Anlong Veng.
While the sun cast long shadows on the parched grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past in the Khmer Rouge.
If the court the convened, she said, she refused to go there.
"Cambodia is peace and stable", "she said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who has defected to the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would happen if the court had several suspects; although the experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past, he said.
But confronting the past is all that Cambodia must do to move forward, said Youk Chhang, the resource centre.
"Reconciliation in Khmer language is to reconnect the broken pieces, he says.
"We must put the pieces together so that we can understand."
The centre has produced the first manual approved by the government on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, composed of 75 pages."
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the history books of the Ministry of Education, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the youth of Anlong Veng know only a few details of the Khmer Rouge, despite links to the city on a diet.
Touch Valeak, 19-year-old student at the high school in Anlong Veng, said that the new manual helped students understand a significant part of their history.
But his parents have reacted with skepticism when he returned with the book at home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court," he says.
"They are wary because they do not know exactly how many people the court continue."
Such resistance has rendered the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok-to Leang said.
But public forums, the manual and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
However, the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful atrait here.
In the heights of Dangrek mountains, a road, invaded by weeds and strewn with plastic bags, led to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty tin roof.
The body of Pol Pot was burned here on a pile of tyres after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, age 31, of mobile phone vendor roadside, said she did not know much about the man who was cremated at this location.
"But it has a great spirit; and many people go there to pray," she says.
It was the anniversary of Nuom Sothea, and later that day, she had planned to walk towards the final resting place of Pol Pot, where she would leave a bouquet of ripe bananas in the hope of bringing the chance.
Belarus agreed to relinquish its stock of weapons-grade uranium
The government of Belarus announced Wednesday that it would abandon its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, an essential component for the nuclear weapons; this decision is part of a surprise victory of the campaign of President Obama to secure nuclear materials in the world
The agreement was disclosed in a joint communiqué issued after Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton met here the Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov, during a summit on security.
The US government had tried for years to convince Belarus to renounce the highly enriched uranium and appeared to have reached the horizon last spring.
But American officials have told the Washington Post that some classified operations have been conducted with Belarus in the past two months to eliminate 187 pounds of weapons-grade uranium from a research centre in Belarus.
This has opened the door to an agreement Wednesday to remove the rest of the field of about £500, according to an official who spoke on the condition of anonymity because of the sensitivity of the issue.
The agreement appears to be one of the most important results of the nuclear security summit of 47 nations, held at the initiative of Obama; where Belarus was excluded.
Apparently, it was beneficial to get an invitation to the former Soviet republic following the summit in 2012.
"I'm really fascinated by the fact that they want a seat at the Nuclear Security Summit Nuclear Security Summit in 2012."
"It shows me that this process works," said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for global security, a group promoting nuclear security.
Clinton called the agreement "very significant step, significant" conducted by Belarus.
Obama has pledged to Prague in April 2009 to secure all vulnerable nuclear material around the world within the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government helped six countries to get rid of all its highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries have done under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of the Nuclear Security Summit of Obama, the Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko, said that the nation would never turn away from its uranium.
"We kept highly enriched uranium, hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially of weapons-grade uranium and the low enriched uranium," said Mr Lukashenko.
"This is our product... We are not going to make dirty bombs, and we will not sell it to anyone."
"We'll use it for research purposes, that is all."
Belarus is closer to the United States a few months ago, however, in showing interest in reaching an agreement.
The first implementation to eliminate uranium from Belarus in October, has been particularly complicated because the material had been slightly unirradiated, officials have said.
It was loaded on a special train has travelled more than 1,300 miles to a facility in Russia to be stored and eliminated, officials have said.
The second operation was completed Monday and was conducted by air, according to the officials.
The US government has spent $13 million in its efforts, in large part to replace research facilities of Belarus with LEU; unsuitable for the weapons.
"A careful coordination and organization have been implemented in order to build confidence"; leading to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, an official of the Department of Energy specialized in the Minimization of the World Endangerment.
According to estimates by the Centre d'Étude of Nonprolifération James Martin, Belarus had this year at least 88 pounds of weapons-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus seeks to eliminate its stockpiles by 2012, according to a joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly because of the harsh crackdown by Lukashenko of Human Rights.
But the statement on Wednesday suggested a potential revival.
"While welcoming the progress on these issues of global security, the United States and Belarus have recognized that increased respect for democracy and Human Rights in Belarus were essential to improve bilateral relations; and essential for the country's progress and its citizens," she said.
