Red Bull triumph in F1 with a secret weapon of Siemens
Software creates improvements on cars, in real time.
As soon as Red Bull es entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this sélecte universe of the speed has been marked by surprise and by the success.
As a first time, nobody has taken into account the options of a new stable just arrived, despite the upward trajectory of recent seasons, the past November, in the last phase of the championship they have all bet on the triumph of Ferrari of Fernando Alonso.
Without lowering the ability as a pilot of the champion, German Sebastien Vette, nor the ability of the Renault engine that drives his car, in the world of Formula 1 it spoke of the legend of "secret weapon" that the multinational company Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to transform it into a winning team.
It is in fact a powerful simulation software to process that the German company was launched on the market in 2007 with very distant goals of the automobilistique top-class.
Appointed PLM, this powerful tool technology has been used to create networks of people who produce assembly plants across the world, power stations, high precision instruments.
The goal is reproduce, accurately simulate the product or the process before the build of a real way, thus avoiding the defects and avoidable costs.
PLM facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or most famous vehicles from Nissan.
Siegfried Russwurm, responsible for the industrial division of Siemens, said the fact that the use of this device technology in its plant in Formula 1 has allowed Red Bull to create and implement "in a few hours, almost in real time," changes, changes and improvements detected during shopping and tests.
Russwurm explains that the stables of the year 1992 had an average of 10 technicians in their teams who was able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements on vehicles each season.
In the Red Bull team now work 180 young professionals of high qualifications which, equipped with powerful computer equipment and analyze planning any kind of changes on the cars.
The leader of Siemens explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all elements of the Red Bull cars except the engine, which is exclusive responsibility of Renault.
It amends the materials, fuel, aerodynamics and security features.
The changes may move from the virtual reality simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced systems of production by autoclaves laser and high technology.
As the only limitation of this madness of technological development there is the $40 million that each team can spend as Formula 1 limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has implanted the high-tech plant to create and produce its cars in a town 50 miles from London.
These are two buildings where the visits, especially for journalists, are limited.
Everything that is happening is considered "top secret".
The staff for this duty in 580 people, enclosed two pilots, the champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of the Red Bull Formula 1, without doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian.
Between the huge technological resources that the mark of energy drinks has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other actors hidden, whose work is invaluable and zero visibility.
The director of technology for the plant, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago you could argue that the progress of R + D in the case of racing cars brought the 50 per cent of victories and the pilots were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have changed and the technology represents the 85% of success, while the pilots apportent the 15% of the value added.
Nevey says the Vettel and Webber will never be replaced by computer, because "they are unpredictable gladiators."
