The Pakistani nuclear program generates great concern in the United States
Islamabad product of atomic weapons to "a faster rate than any other country."
The leaching of Wikileaks confirmed the connection between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the US Embassy in Pakistan and the Department of State of the United States filtered through the portal Wikileaks confirms the enormous preoccupation in Washington on Pakistan's nuclear program.
Apart from the details illuminating and tasty that offer on the content of the conversations and thoughts of North American diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal the fact that cooperation between the two countries in the field of nuclear security, instead of increasing, "decreases" and that the volatile Asian country produces nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - the fact that the weapons are not assemblies, but they are emmagasinnées by components to complicate their destruction in case of attack - is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
It is as well that the ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, listed in a report before the visit of former National Security Advisor, James Jones: "the proximity of some nuclear facilities of the territory under attack Taliban, the spread of nuclear materials including noise short and the vulnerability of transport of atomic materials".
The large number of people involved in the nuclear arsenals and the curricula of missiles is considered, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, and proliferating as a reason to maintain the custody.
"Pakistan has the hire staff with the strict religious beliefs to protect the nuclear facilities; given the decline of cultural and educational levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who worked in the nuclear programs or missiles," said the expert Yuri Korolev, the Ministry of External Russian for a meeting with its American counterparts.
The new documentation filtered through the portal of Julian Assange is increasingly reduced cooperation between the United States and Pakistan in the field of nuclear proliferation and the high level of production of Pakistani nuclear armas.
A dispatch from the Embassy in May, which qualifies as "frustrating" communication with Pakistan, argues that "transparency is frequently non-existent; the offers of assistance remain unanswered or are eliminated".
In another message, Peter Lavoy, official of the National Intelligence for South Asia, said that "despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
Ambassador Patterson also calls in Washington, during a visit by the head of the Army, General Ashfaq Kayani, understanding that it is "very clearly" in charge that "the Army of Pakistan should end with the tacit support to terrorist groups".
