Obama promotes in the law in favour of undocumented students
"If you agreed with the approval of the Act Dream Act, calls silent senators and ask them to approve this legislation," Twitté US president in the popular social network.
President Barack Obama is meeting today at the national mobilization to support the Act Dream Act, to legalize undocumented students, with a message in his personal account of the social network Twitter.
"If you agreed with the approval of the Act Dream Act, calls silent senators and ask them to approve this legislation," Twitté Obama.
The short message is keeping open a cyber relationship with a document further who asks the public to immediately contact the senators, as the vote on the legislation is imminent.
"With a vote that they hope soon, now is the time to listen to your voice," he says.
The message was disclosed after the 42 Republican senators have threatened to block the vote of any legislation if the extension of tax cuts from the time of Bush and the financing of government is protracted.
Such a freeze, announced in a letter signed by all 41 Republican senators, could affect the vote of the Act Dream Act and other projects as the ratification of the new START treaty with Russia against the proliferation of nuclear weapons.
Asked about the Republican blocking the Act Dream Act and other projects, the presidential spokesman Robert Gibbs said he is confident that once the tax problem is solved we can fix a agende for the rest of the projects.
"I think it was a lot of time..."
"We all agree that we must resolve this tax issue before the end of the year..."
"I think we can get an agreement at a given moment in this direction and then we can plan the sequence of the rest," he says.
The leader of the Democratic majority in the Senate, Harry Reid, announced Tuesday it would seek a "vote of the debate" to the Act Dream Act, which is why the initiative to legalize undocumented students could be passed from next Thursday in the Senate, although the most likely would be next week.
The Senate version of the Dream Act or the Law of Rêve American legalize 800 thousand young people who arrived in the United States before the age of 16, they remained in the country in the past five years and they have been accepted by an institution of higher education or by the Army.
But the supporters need 60 votes to approve the initiative, which is why they need the support of a large number of Republicans, in times when the partisan organizations project protagonists intense lobbying to ensure the approval of the Act.
The Democrats, the majority of which supports the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
But at least one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, said he would vote against and only a Republican expressed its support for the law, Richard Lugar of Indiana.
It is for this that supporters of the Dream Act requires the vote of several Republicans if other aviserne Democrats vote against the initiative.
Among Republicans the most courted there are senators Maine, Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, and the outgoing Senator George Lemieux, Florida, which completed the mandate su Senator Mel Martinez.
Other Republicans who have supported in the past the Dream Act are Orrin Hatch of Utah, and Kay Bailey Hutchinson, of Texas, but they have said they would not support it in another opportunity.
Another Republican who has supported John McCain, did not define its position so far.
Even if the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree with the fact that the greater challenges of the Dream Act are in the Senate.
