The bill curators who, according to the government, should address the problem of ships laden with illegal migrants, will obviously be beaten when the three opposition parties have reported Wednesday that they could not support it.
"I strongly support on the charter."
"I am standing with a party that has created the granite under your feet," said the Liberal leader Michael Ignatieff, when he was surrounded by deputies after the weekly meeting of the caucus.
Liberals argue that the bill as proposed, which would own up to one year, a person from a ship identified as carrying illegal immigrants, would violate the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
The Bloc Quebecois leader Gilles Duceppe, also indicated that it could not support the bill because it took on the wrong target.
"We are against and it seems that all the opposition parties are against, then we will see what the government will do," said Mr. Duceppe.
The criticism of the NPD in immigration, Olivia Chow, rejected out of hand the criticism that his party is not tough enough on illegal immigrants.
"The New Democrats agree to take measures against the smugglers and that is what we are doing through another bill, the C-35," said Ms. Chow.
"We do not support the bill conservatives because it takes to refugees and imprisoning the children for at least a year," explained Ms. Chow.
The Immigration Minister Jason Kenney, has accused the opposition parties to play politics and to ignore the will of Canadians.
