The new unit does not unanimous support
Despite the announcement of the possible creation of a permanent unit to combat corruption and collusion by Jean Charest, many observers continue to call for the creation of a public inquiry on the subject.
The Minister of Public Safety, Robert Dutil, argues that this idea is not new: Quebec would have consulted the Department of Investigation in New York in this regard as early as January.
The metropolis has a permanent unit on corruption since 1870.
However, the announcement Tuesday, has surprised many.
It must be said that at a meeting of the Permanent Council on the police, Quebec, on 29 October, this measure has never been discussed despite the presence of Robert Dutil.
It does not need more if the péquiste critical public safety, Stéphane Bergeron, called the announcement "rabbit out of a hat" and "bricolée solution on the corner of a table."
The Minister Dutil went responded to those who fear that political power has too much influence on the possible future unit.
"You will see the result when we will announce it, contente-t-il to say."
"We are aware of this problem."
For the president of the CSQ, Réjean Fullick, nothing can replace the establishment of a public inquiry.
"More Mr Charest insists on not wanting to create this commission of inquiry, the more people think like you and me that he has something to hide," he explains.
"The only way to have a commission of inquiry is the resignation of Jean Charest," says about him Yves Boisvert, professor of ethics and governance at the National School of Public Administration.
To break the impasse, it suggests in Quebec to give a special mandate the Auditor General to investigate collusion and corruption.
"We must be able to expand the mandate of the Auditor General," tranche-t-il.
He also believes that Quebec could give the auditor the same powers as a commissioner, allowing him to force people to testify.
The creation of a permanent squad is not the only project in the boxes of Government Charest.
Quebec also ask to Ottawa to amend the Criminal Code to be better suited to this type of crime.
This request came from the prosecutor of the operation Marteau, who informed the Minister of Justice Jean-Marc Fournier that jurisprudence is not explicit in such investigations.
The Federal Minister of Public Safety, Vic Toews, has meanwhile confirmed that his colleague of Justice, Rob Nicholson, is currently studying some amendments relating to this issue.
During Operation Spring 2001, on biker groups, even if the Criminal Code was not suitable, 131 people were arrested.
Ottawa has subsequently passed the Law on gangsterism.
Scrutiny rivers surveillance
Several rivers remain under scrutiny because of the heavy rains that have hit several areas of the province since Tuesday.
A landslide occurred Wednesday afternoon, Shawinigan, Mauricie.
Two homes were evacuated preemptively.
In the evening, another landslide occurred in Saint-Lin-Laurentides, in Lanaudière.
A Road has collapsed.
From Tuesday to Wednesday evening, heavy rain have hit several areas, from 40 to 70 millimetres of rain.
20 To 40 millimetres of rain were expected by Thursday evening, according to the regions.
The areas north of the river and Outaouais in the valley were most affected.
They could receive up to 100 mm of rain in total.
As we must add this precipitation to the melting of the snow already accumulated in some sectors, there are fears the spillover of several rivers.
Flood alert warnings have been issued on Wednesday evening by the civil security of Quebec to rivers Ouareau and'Achigan in Lanaudière.
The Northern Rivers, Saint-Jérôme, Laurentides, and in the oak in Lotbinière, for their part, were the subject of flood watches and remained under supervision.
In the region of Lanaudière, heavy rain led to flooding in some lakes, Sainte-Julienne, Sainte-Marcelline-de-Kildare and Rawdon.
At Saint-Calixte, a temporary bridge was washed away because of heavy rains.
Ten homes had to be evacuated as a preventative measure.
In Outaouais, the spillover of some lakes has led to the closing of several roads, particularly in the municipality of Mansfield-et-Pontefract.
The civil security remains on high alert and is monitoring the situation closely, said Annik Bouchard, conseillère safe.
The flood forecasting Centre of Quebec, for its part, has issued Wednesday of severe flooding warnings for several rivers, including Maskinongé, Assomption, Ouareau, the'Achigan, Batiscan and Wolf.
DuPont partiellement blamé
The radio host of Quebec Stéphane Dupont partial suffered a setback before the Canadian Broadcast Standards Council (CCNR) for controversial statements on social assistance and Haitians and on its foul language on air.
The CCNR judge that Mr. Dupont and his team of 98.1 NOH FM had the right to express their opinions, but that certain statements contained "the inaccurate information on social assistance, negative unduly representations of Haitians and the coarse language which is not suitable for broadcast during the day."
The Council also concluded that a discussion about suicide, including the release of the names of two people who had suicide, did not breach broadcasting codes.
The CCNR had received several complaints about comments made during programs broadcast between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made in response to a complaint of Common Front social of Quebec.
The group complained that the amounts cited in the show were inaccurate.
Leaders must be solid rather than misleading.
On suicide, the moderator Stéphane Dupont had found that suicide is a gesture of cowardly.
The majority of members of the Committee concluded that the message was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to the problems of life.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the episodes involved Dupont lunch" addressed a delicate subject fairly and appropriately. "
No blame has therefore been held against her.
The latest dispute was on statements that followed the earthquake in Haiti.
Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort were then delivered to a media standoff that had been a great deal of response.
The facilitator of NOH said he made no donation to help the Haitians because we could not know with certainty that the truly needy people would receive the money.
The Committee believes that these comments were not abusive, but their cumulative effect is a negative unfair representation of Haitians.
"I have served my suspension of three days about it."
"My file is blank for a year and a half," said the host.
In all decisions, the Committee denounced the dissemination of coarse language.
In each case, the broadcaster CHOI-FM collaborated "beyond its obligation".
The consequences are minimal for the station, which will, among other things, announce these decisions once during the primetime within three days.
A king of kung-fu in Montreal
The Montréalais of Algerian origin Nacereddine Zemmal has a very particular route.
The athlete who excels in "sanda" (kung-fu "full contact"), and Thai boxing Kickboxing rises on the tatami mats and the rings of the world in search of new challenges.
"I started practicing martial arts as the kung-fu and kickboxing 12 years ago, in Algeria, explained Zemmal, installed in the city since 2008 to move among professionals."
"In my case, I am fighting everywhere, as for those who do not like the ground game in this mixed martial arts, the competitions are rare in North America."
Recently, the one who works as a security officer and as committed to the company UPS has just issued bad news to its rivals, winning two gold medals at the World Championships of the World Karate and Kickboxing Association (WKA), from 23 to 30 October, in Edinburgh, Scotland.
"I won the categories of Kickboxing full contact and Thai boxing," he explained. "
"Right now, I am preparing to go to China for the World Cup in san shou."
"Fighters who have finished in the top four at the last world championships in each category were invited."
"I've won bronze in 2009 in Toronto."
"In 2005, Vietnam, I finished eighth.
"In 2007, China, I found the tournament to fifth, while I came third in Toronto in 2009," he said.
"What is interesting is that I have increased in every competition."
"At this rate, I will be first or this time next year!"
The "san shou" or "sanda" is a discipline from China where the punches and kicks, as well as the projections on the ground, are permitted.
The shootouts are on a platform and more rarely in a ring.
The most famous pugiliste from this form of combat is the American of Vietnamese origin Cung Le, well known in the world of martial arts.
If Nacer Zemmal did to remember that a single event in his career, he will certainly its presence in Super tournament "King of Sanda", the Super Bowl of the kung-fu.
"This competition is the more fierce and most prestigious in China, explained the foc sympathetic."
"This is just the equivalent of the Lumpinee Stadium (the biggest stage of Thailand."
"It was a great experience."
Zemmal won his first semi-final struggle in its category (80 kg), before losing in the final.
"Anyone who has defeated me was a true pro, he analyzed."
"There are four combatants by category (80 kg, 85 kg, 90 kg and 90 kg)."
"The winners in the semi-finals final clash in their category."
"Then the winners of each category will face only to crown a champion, the King of kung-fu."
450 Million in contracts without bidding
'Hydro-Québec Gave over-thecounter 450 million in contracts to firms of engineering for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts, it is a consortium of firms BPR, Dessau, SM Group Axor and won the most important, that the management of the project, for a sum of $295 million without bidding.
This consortium called Énergie stewardship has been formed in 2004 concomitantly the choice of Hydro-Québec to the private sector its responsibility to manage this important hydroelectric project of $5 billion.
In early 2005, the Energy consortium won the lucrative contract without there has been no public tender.
For the Party québécois, the use of business Consortiums poses a serious problem'éthique threatening to eliminate competition and drive up prices.
"This is the new way of making collusion and kill competition."
"It means that people, instead of making it a secret, now do so openly," said yesterday the MP yesterday péquiste Sylvain Simard in press conference.
Earlier in the morning, Mr. Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because it is difficult to see how the public interest can be used this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded by afternoon, vigorously denying that there has been collusion for this contract.
"I am beginning to have my trip," she pesté, arguing that the PQ had been "dishonest" and had "lacked rigour".
She said that "it would be the least of things" that the PQ apologizes.
The Consortiums formula is a common practice in the world.
It is usually a limited alliance in the time allowed two or more companies to combine their respective expertise to meet a tender for a complex project.
The Mistissini project contains a high level of complexity given the scale of work.
The site is under way and should run until 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without competition'agisse; there has been negotiations.
Also, the Consortiums formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for projects relatively simple.
As revealed last week, the formula of Le Devoir Consortiums in the engineering sector was being investigated the Government.
A quick survey of the Register of Quebec can count more than 200 consortia, some of which appear to be permanent.
Thus, the firm Dessau is working in partnership with most of its main competitors, including CIJL +, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin and other Roche and Tecsult.
Each combination, and there are dozens, back to a single entity or Dessau.
In terms of the consortium stewardship, the Minister Normandeau stressed that "the territory of the James Bay meets specific dynamic workforce and'Hydro-Québec responds in particular since the 1970s".
The boss of the Mistissini project, Réal Laporte, the James Bay Energy Corporation (SEBJ), gave an explanation that frowned on the fact that the management agreement of the project management contract was awarded over-thecounter.
"If you're going to bidding and that there are few bidders, your prices will be higher."
"You have two choices: either you take people who are in this market and you say: we will negotiate a satisfactory agreement and with a good price."
"But the idea is that this is not the price that is important is the quality of the people," said Mr. Laporte.
The contract awarded to the consortium Énergie stewardship is part of a long list of contracts of more than $50,000 obtained by the Party québécois.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the project Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert.
After verification, Le Devoir were 109 engineering contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to firms or their subsidiaries, including soil laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin beat 22 contracts, Génivar won 16, 14 and 10 Tecsult Dessau, not to mention her participation in Énergie stewardship.
All contracts were negotiated.
They totaled $12,783 449,358 783 344, including the contract to'Énergie stewardship of 295 131 $564.00.
Sylvain Simard suggested that the four firms that make up the consortium (OPIs, Dessau, Group DM and Axor) are "well known in Quebec Liberal Party".
The Minister Normandeau dropped that the PQ is also linked to these firms that the "financent", he added that it was more a case of its leaders.
Barometer of responsible consumption - The "Green" does not inspire confidence
Greener, but frankly skeptical.
The consumer québécois very little confidence in the actors of sustainable development, but also to marks equitableand to écologisantes certifications to guide its choice.
Worse, even if it is bathed in a media universe where messages for a more responsible consumption abound, he regretted a lack of credible information, carence that it is even brake on its commitment, barometer indicates the responsible consumption, including the first reading was delivered yesterday.
Even if they have increased the consumption of so-called socially responsible products in 2010, Quebecers seem to give little credit to those who are trying to sell them.
Two thirds of them say indeed not believe environmental commitment of companies like green advertising companies, reveals the measurement tool developed by the Observatory of the responsible consumption of the University Sherbrooke.
Another finding: half of consumers questioned the reliability of official certification affixed to the so-called fair products, but also the credibility of products and brands if displaying as écoresponsables, said the Barometer.
In the same vein, the politicians' rhetoric on this theme is taken seriously by only 14.6 percent of Quebecers.
Information about responsible consumption, however, seems paramount to stimulate this part of the lively consumption by nearly one-third of consumers québécois.
Indeed, the vacuum and the dubious nature of the information calmeraient the ardour of 46 per cent of consumers.
This is the second identified by the brake Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, a third of Quebecers are also wary of the alleged performance of green products or services sought to put their hands.
On another note, consumers have been almost half in 2010 to have changed their habit and especially changed mark of one or more products to meet their conviction.
At height of 61%, they have also promoted purchases with traders in their neighbourhood and privileged the food grown in their region, said the Barometer.
Greener and responsible - the index of responsible consumption reached 64 on a maximum of 100 for this year - Homo consumus of Quebec likes to present itself as the king of recycling that seeks to reduce its environmental footprint focusing on the protection of animals.
But his social conscience and ecological appears, however, remain outside his car, said the Barometer: in 2010, just 28% of Québécois reported having used public transportation or called for carpooling to defend their interests green.
Walking and cycling were also supported by 39.1% of participants in the comprehensive behavioral survey, which has just taken its first cliché.
