But Christian Yaccarini has not recalled Le Devoir and it is unclear what he and his group believe proposals to the decline of which they are made.
The lifted the veil on a Canada complexed...
The new US diplomatic cables released by WikiLeaks lift the veil on what the United States consider the inferiority complex of Canadians with the Americans, but they betray at the same time the sense of superiority of them to Canada.
For example, American diplomats are surprised that each voter has not Canada-U.S. relations in mind voting, and believe that the visit of President Obama has helped the Conservative government to adopt its budget in 2009!
The four new communications between the U.S. Embassy in Ottawa and Washington over the public yesterday, offer more titbits that content to come under the tooth.
A cable dated September 22, 2008, is in full federal election campaign, recounts how the United States are not part of the issues discussed by political leaders.
To the astonishment of the American ambassador based in Ottawa, David Wilkins.
Mr. Wilkins offers some explanation for this situation.
"A Canadian inferiority complex almost inherent is, perhaps the Canadian political leaders to talk about domestic challenges of everyday life rather than to wear this election on the United States (as in the campaign on free trade in 1988)," he writes.
The United States is, he adds, "the proverbial elephant in this election: ubiquitous, but potentially too threatening to talk".
The ambassador is even less the "deafening silence" that the two countries have an intense political and economic relationship.
"Logically, he says, the ability of a candidate, a party and even more of a party leader to manage this critical relationship should be a key factor that voters have in mind in voting."
Another expression of this sense of importance reads in the cable sent on 22 January 2009 by Terry Breese, chargé d'affaires in Ottawa, preparing President Barack Obama on his first visit to Ottawa.
"Your trip will help ensure the survival of the government in early February the vote of confidence on the federal budget, by which Canada will post its first deficit in more than a decade due to a stimulus package of $30 billion to $40 billion," writes Mr Breese.
Nowhere does it mention that the government had to prorogue Parliament before Christmas to avoid being ousted by the coalition and the opposition parties made its survival conditional on the quality of the proposed stimulus plan.
Another communication, dated January 2008 and signed by Ambassador Wilkins, warns Washington the increasingly negative image that the drama series aired on CBC refer to the United States.
The ambassador is concerned about emissions Border, Little Mosque on the Prairie, Intelligence and H2O, in which there is little subtle references to Maher Arar, the "No-Fly-List" or abductions for CIA interrogations.
Another cable said that, during their first bilateral meeting, Hillary Clinton asked his French counterpart Bernard Kouchner if Europe was ready to accept some Guantánamo prisoners.
Mr. Kouchner said yes, but on the basis of "case by case".
At the end of the meeting, is it writing, "he presented a paper to the Secretary of State about Omar Khadr, a Muslim of 15 years of Canadian origin."
"The secretary agreed to review the file".
Lastly, the minds heated up on the site WikiLeaks.
Tom Flanagan, a former adviser very close to Stephen Harper, said on CBC that the responsible for this massive flight should be "murdered".
It echoed Mike Huckabee in the United States.
A Global plan to renovate Lighting
The United Nations has proposed yesterday to Cancún a renovation plan of the domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries in order to achieve a reduction of greenhouse gases (GHG), which corresponds to almost one-third of the additional reduction that we need to achieve to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
The ambitious plan is in the wake of large concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that monopolize yet 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by bulbs or, better, by blisters to light-emitting diodes (LEDs or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tonnes (GtCO2) of GHG issued on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the largest emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, are engaged in voluntary reduction plans that are projected to reduce overall emissions of GHGs 53 GtCO2 to 49 GtCO2.
But he will remove this bilan still 5 GtCO2 in order to stabilize by 2020 the climate increase to 2 degrees Celsius to avoid it gets out of control.
In the incandescent light bulbs, 95% of energy dissipates as heat and the rest, or 5%, a product of the light.
With the bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, it reduces the need energy twice.
The bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those that launched the manufacturer Philips this week - the company has also participated in the study of the United Nations - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the economy as possible with an alternative plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all new bulbs can also work with rhéostats in addition to issue very little heat.
And they do not contain mercury.
Several specialists have posted reservations against the bulbs because they contain mercury and that we must eliminate them as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place orders.
But, says the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent light bulbs.
The United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 metric tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that would each country through the international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2, or the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power stations whose construction would be 2.5 billion.
The Côte d'Ivoire waits in the nervousness the announcement of election results
The UN Secretary-General, Ban Ki-moon, claimed the publication "without delay" the results of the presidential election in Côte d'Ivoire, after the expiry of the deadline.
"The Secretary-General underlines the need for the independent electoral commission to complete its work and to announce interim results without further delay," said a spokesman for the head of the United Nations. "
"He calls on all parties and the institutions to act responsibly and refrain from any initiative until the announcement of preliminary results."
Despite pressure from some foreign governments, the electoral commission has missed the deadline of midnight without publish the results, three days after the polling of Sunday.
About 40 minutes before the deadline, the chairman of the IEC had said on television that the commission "continued to work" to announce the results.
The calls have increased Wednesday in the world for the CIS redetermines finally the name of the winner of the second round between the incumbent Laurent Gbagbo and Alassane Ouattara the opponent.
But the camp Gbagbo relies on the cancellation by the Constitutional Council votes "fraudulent" in the north, held by the former rebel forces of the New Forces (FN) since the failed coup of September 2002.
Pascal Affi N'Guessan, campaign manager of the Ivorian president, said that the intimidation of voters practised by the NFs in the north of the country had discouraged supporters of the outgoing president to vote.
The election could be cancelled if the complaints filed by Gbagbo are retained by the Constitutional Council.
Yet opponents of Gbagbo believe that the highest court in the country is not neutral because it is directed by Paul Yao N Dré, a close political ally of Gbagbo.
Alassane Ouattara, North man who denies any link with the former rebels, has deemed "unacceptable" the delay in announcing the results and called on Gbagbo to respect them, but it is not gone so far as to claim victory.
Its allies claim that Gbagbo is blocking the publication of results because he knows that he has lost and that complain to the Constitutional Council, having prevented the electoral commission to release the results, would be illegal.
The second round of the presidential elections, Sunday, was supposed to top the process of reunification and reconciliation to a country remained divided into two for years.
The United Nations warned Wednesday the Ivorian political class that it could be held responsible for any violence.
Laurent Gbagbo had finished at the top of the first round, on 31 October, with 38% of the vote against 32 per cent to Alassane Ouattara, who received the public support of the former President Henri Konan Bédié (25 per cent in the first round.
The unemployment rate remained stable in France in the 3rd Quarter
The unemployment rate in France within the meaning of the International Labour Office (ILO) has remained stable at 9.3% in metropolitan France (9.7% including the overseas departments), show the seasonally adjusted (CVS) provisoires published Thursday by INSEE.
The number of unemployed is 2,631 million in metropolitan France.
Data from the second quarter were confirmed at 9.3% of the working population in metropolitan France and 9.7% with the DOMs.
In a year, the unemployment rate is rising 0.1 point.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they are available in the two weeks to work and that they are looking for a job.
The situation of young people in the labour market has deteriorated further, with a further increase in the unemployment rate increased to 24.2% in metropolitan France (+ 0.9 point on three months, + 0.5 point on a year) and 25% including the DOMs.
In the third quarter, 637 million young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed within the meaning of the ILO.
The seniors have known for their share a slight rise in unemployment, to 6.4% in metropolitan France (+ 0.2 points in three months and a year) or 482 000 people 50 years or more, and 6.6% with the DOMs.
Only the 25-49 years have benefited from the stability of unemployment in the third quarter, to 8.3% in metropolitan France (-0.1 point on three months, + 0.1 point on a year) and 8.8% throughout France.
INSEE does not publish more monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after an argument on its methodology.
Eurostat, the statistics agency of the European Union, continues in contrast to do so and announced Tuesday a rate of 9.8 per cent in France (DOMs included) in October after 9.9% in September.
