The South Korean government will adopt a law known as the "Cinderella" that will ban teens playing games on-line after midnight by blocking their access, said government officials.
A bill will be submitted to Parliament in December to request the online game companies to block access to these games after midnight, youth under the age of 16, said representatives of the ministries of culture and family.
"A lot of children play in these games all night and then difficult to study at school and have a normal life during the day."
"We believe that this law is needed to ensure their health and their right to sleep," said AFP Jo Rin Ministerial-level, the official in charge of the bill.
Online games will be available again at 6 a.m.
Companies will have a year to prepare for the implementation of the law, he said.
The government is also considering asking the companies to limit the time daily access to these games for young people whose parents demand, added the official.
It will also make available to the people who need free software that will limit the time spent on the Internet.
South Korea is one of the countries most "connected" and newspapers regularly report facts related to various intensive use of the Internet.
The country is also the undisputed champion of world events online gambling.
In November, South Korea had won four gold medals at the World Cyber Games, with 58 other nations.
