European sovereign debt crisis requires, the institute of Frankfurt may not afford to be in such a sweeping only worsen a situation more than tense today on the European bond markets.
The political costs would be even higher.
Yesterday, at a press conference, the French Finance Minister, Christine Lagarde, has also welcomed the active role played by the ECB in favour of the resolution of the crisis of debts of states in Europe.
She was unwilling to say whether she believed that the central bank should do more, such as increasing its sovereign bond purchase program.
"I reserve my reflection in my European partners (...)".
The day before, in Brussels, during his hearing by the Economic and Monetary Affairs Committee of the European Parliament, the President of the ECB, Jean-Claude Trichet, did not show more disert about his intentions, saying only that the programme of buying government securities in the secondary market "continued," and that "we will see what we decide" at the meeting this Thursday.
One certainty: the ECB will keep its main interest rate unchanged at 1 per cent, its lowest level ever since May 2009.
In fact, purchases of government bonds by the ECB have doubled last week, to nearly 1.35 billion euros.
And, according to the indiscretions of market participants, it would have made new purchases of securities purchases Irish and Portuguese, yesterday.
In total, the central banks of the eurosystème purchased $67 billion euros since May 2010.
Among market participants, expectations of further purchases are no doubt (see page 29).
Not most economists do not expect significant change of course.
If the loans to more than three months have already disappeared from the arsenal of the ECB, the past is still to allowances of unlimited liquidity on the conditions and generous for periods from a week to three months.
Economists now expect that the scheme to be extended by a few months.
"I cannot imagine that it alters significantly its programme."
"Otherwise it would take the risk of provoking new tensions in the short term," said Michael Schubert, economist at Commerzbank.
"A gradual exit announced during the first quarter 2011 seems more likely," anticipates its side Norbert Bräms, an economist at Sal.
Oppenheim.
In terms of its interventions on the debt markets, "the ECB should maintain a volume of purchase these obligations to animate a sluggish market," said Norbert Bräms.
Given the importance of European banks' exposure to markets of sovereign debt in the eurozone, the institute of issuance has no other choice than to maintain its presence in the market.
"It must at all costs be a substitute for lack of investors in the market and act so to prevent a runaway yields paid by the most fragile States", was an important bond manager yesterday.
Because if interest rates are soaring, the States will be even more embarrassed to reduce their debt, if not stabilize it.
The protection of the euro is at this price.
