Hackers spies and spies in diligence
The case of WikiLeaks has a dual value.
On one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as scandal before the hypocrisy that governs the relationship between the states, citizens and the press.
On the other, she announced sweeping changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by the downturn.
But are in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks, it is confirmation of the fact that each file compiled by a secret service (of any nation that it is) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about the sexual habits of Berlusconi only report which for months could be read in any newspaper (except those whose Berlusconi owns), and the eerily Profile caricature of Al-Qadhafi was long for the cabaret artists matière to sketch.
The rule that the secret files must be that new compounds already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore on esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeat (on the Holy Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the or the Rose-Croix Temple) exactly what was already written in the previous books.
And not only because the author of hidden texts does not like to make unpubl. research (nor knows where to look for news on the non-existent), but because those involved in the occult, only to what they already know, and reconfirms what they had learned.
It is the mechanism of the success of Dan Brown.
Ditto for the secret Files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or spirit limited) the head of the secret services (otherwise it might be, that sais-je, editor of Libération), which does as true that what he recognizes.
The top secret information on Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome sent to the State Department were the same as those that Newsweek published the week before.
So why the revelations on these issues have made so much noise?
On one hand, they say what any educated person knows already, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the Heads of States can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic service and, except for a few small representation exercises, have turned into centres of espionage.
Any viewer of films ofinquiry knows this, and it is only by hypocrisy that it pretends to ignore it.
However, the fact of the say publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and is used to place in a bad light American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker can get any secrets more secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
As the scandal does not so much in crisis the victims that the "torturers".
But now to the very nature of what happened.
Once, at the time of Orwell, one could conceive of any power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy was completely proved since, that can monitor each movement through the phone, every transaction, the hotel visited the motorway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it happens now, that even the crypts of secrets of power cannot escape the scrutiny of a hacker, the audit report ceases to be able and becomes circular.
The power control every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as avenger of the citizen - can know all the secrets of power.
How a power that no longer has the opportunity to retain its own can hold secrets?
It is true, Georg Simmel said already, that a true secret is a secret empty (and secret vacuum can never be unveiled); it is true, too, that know everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually a secret vacuum of secret, because in the public domain; but reveal, as did WikiLeaks, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secret means removing any power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy and Merkel, but has done too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, the states can no longer put online any information given - it would publish it on a poster pasted on the street corner.
But it is equally clear that with the current technology, it is vain hope to maintain confidential reports by telephone.
Nothing easier than to discover if and when a head of state has shifted in aircraft and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can be maintained in the future private reports and reserved?
I know that, for the moment, my anticipation is science fiction and is therefore novels, but I am forced to imagine government officials who move quietly buggy in the uncontrollable routes, by not being that carry messages learned by heart or, at most, by hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be stored in a single copy in drawers locked: basically, the attempted espionage of the Watergate had less successful that WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now in crabe, i.e. backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, Internet has restored a telegraph on son (voice).
The analog (video-cassettes) had allowed the researchers to explore a film step by step, by going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of the assembly, but now the CD (digital) do that to jump chapter by chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, it goes from Rome to Milan in three hours, while in air travel, and it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is not extraordinary that the policy and communications technology in return for cars.
A final comment.
Previously, the press was trying to understand what was going in the secrecy of embassies.
Now, it is the embassies are seeking confidential information to the press.
Weather: how France bidouille its promises of funding
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the basis of promises of funding quickly released (so-called fast start funding early funding) made by the developed countries.
And big French bidouillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries have pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised 7,2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (including 420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU took out the great game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to the fast start funding: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, great side event, distribution of brochures...
The operation transparency is welcome and Embraced: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries do the same with the same level of detail.
The EU announced have reached 2.2 billion euros in 2010, which puts it on the way to respect its commitment to 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional", to ensure that an extra effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what it means to "new and additional".
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some member states including France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
The European Commission has, for example, regarded as a reference the year 2009: international funding are maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years under funding fast start.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or in terms of the level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France believes that the funding of "all new projects" the year 2010 are "new and additional".
In other words, there was no reference to previous years' expenses or the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of support of France to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), she claimed its commitment to funding "new and additional"...
Another crucial element, the distribution of grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses its calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that 1 €Loaned amounts to €1.
Of course, this is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigating emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is disingenuous to present a euro that it will recover as equivalent to a euro that it gives... Any at most, should not be counted under its commitments that the cost of borrowing for the country lender (equivalent to a rate of interest).
But France did that make such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros in doing 91.5% of loans (389,8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only EU country to use if heavily the loan.
Germany are requiert to 46 per cent, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (other) respect their commitments with 100% of donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union is €1 to meet its commitment, France does that 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice trick!
In summary, in its financing fast start, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action in time and on the other hand, the financial reality of the effort.
By not spending that 36.1 million euros, it comes to believe that she spends 420 million "new and additional" consistent with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because, it seems that it is Bercy that has made the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why other States members would continue to give it is sufficient to lend?) and in the negotiations because the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter of early funding is not a small issue, on short term compared to overall discussions on the climate.
But it could be a grain of sand in the vast machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
Nevertheless, it is essential to learn the lessons of this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in the way of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect its commitments and equity with other EU countries.
But above all, France could advance discussions on issues of long-term financing (other crucial chapter currently being discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the accounting treatment loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues than it is in others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on the fast start of France and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence necessary for progress in the discussions.
Alert to pesticides ingested by Children
A 10-year-old child ingests in a day 81 different chemicals, according to a study published Wednesday of the association Generations Futures (ex- Movement for Rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no statistically significant value under the low number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with", purchased between July and September foods generally consumed in four meals and a snack in a day by a child a decade in supermarkets the Oise and Paris.
These meals types, including the official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - as well as candy, were examined by laboratories in search of chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet of the base is overwhelming: 81 chemicals including 42 are classified and five possible or probable cancer-causing substances that are carcinogenic some and 37 substances that act as endocrine disrupters (RIs), according to studies of several institutions such as the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
"Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical substance taken individually, are not exceeded, it is clear in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants possibly carcinogenic and / or PE is worrying," notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven Carcinogens as carcinogenic some as well as nearly 20 Residues likely disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as snack by the study, shows signs of six chemicals including a fungicide yet banned in France.
Same thing for green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the steak haché, canned tuna, and even the loaves of bread and the chewing gum were littered with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water the analysis revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the consideration of the plastic base used to warm the microwave meals in was not free.
The final risk to the consumer of this "contaminants" cocktails "is probably underestimated", according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Greens (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "given the urgency of the situation" a moratorium on the use of pesticides, to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
